  "nodes": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/claim/cou1-hemolysis-worst-case",
      "type": "Claim",
      "name": "CFD model identifies worst-case hemolysis operating conditions for CPB device",
      "description": "The CFD model of the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump is credible for identifying the worst-case hemolysis operating condition among the five evaluated flow-speed combinations under CPB use conditions. This conclusion is grounded in the complete 13-factor ASME V&V 40 credibility assessment, mesh convergence studies demonstrating GCI below 2.5%, turbulence model benchmarking against published FDA pump data from Hariharan et al. (2011) and Stewart et al. (2012), and experimental hemolysis measurements from the NIH/FDA interlaboratory study. The power-law hemolysis model (Giersiepen-Wurzinger) was calibrated against bovine blood data and cross-validated against porcine blood results. All seven assessed credibility factors meet or exceed the required gradation level for MRL 2. The relative hemolysis index criterion (RH < 1) is satisfied across all operating points, with the 6 L/min at 3500 RPM condition identified as the worst-case scenario (RH = 0.82). The body of computational and experimental evidence collectively supports the claim that the model output is sufficiently credible for the regulatory submission decision described in COU1.",
      "scope": "FDA generic centrifugal blood pump; CPB operating envelope; 5 flow-speed combinations; Class II device classification; MRL 2 credibility requirements"
    }
  ],
